<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-22T22:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-22T22:00:00-05:00" n="472" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d472">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Bullitt, William C./551:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-22T22:00:00-05:00">December 22, 1939—10
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>1559. Your 3023, December 21, 8 p.m. From the President and the
                                Secretary. Daladier is asking us to assume greater responsibility
                                than is possible. Practically speaking it might well react against
                                the very purpose he has in mind. Please make this clear to him and
                                explain why we cannot order you home at this time but will do so
                                when Kennedy<note n="60" xml:id="d472fn60">Joseph P. Kennedy,
                                    Ambassador in the United Kingdom.</note> returns to London.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>